#### 4.9.3 Archimedes' Principle

Archimedes' Principle informs us on how to determine upthrust:

Archimedes' Principle states that when an object is totally or partially immersed in a fluid, it experiences a net upward force (upthrust) equal in magnitude and opposite in direction to the **weight of fluid displaced**.

i.e. Uphrrust = Weight of fluid displaced

U = m\({}_{\text{fl.\ displ}}\)g = p\({}_{\text{f}}\)V\({}_{\text{fl.\ displ.}}\)g

Where: U is upthrust acting on the object (N)

p\({}_{\text{f}}\) is density of fluid displaced (kg m\({}^{3}\))

g is gravitational acceleration (m s\({}^{-2}\))

V\({}_{\text{fl.\ displ.}}\) is volume of fluid displaced (m\({}^{3}\))

Upthrust exists for both an object that is floating and object that is sinking

- When it is **sinking**, means that:

Weight > Uphrrust

- When it is **floating**, means that:

Weight = Uphrrust

